h care to assisted living to community-based hospice to adult day services. These models are, for most, preferable to nursing homes and allow older adults to “age in place”—live longer in their own homes and communities. Home- and Community-Based Services for Older Adults examines the existing and emerging models of HCBS, including the history, theory, research, policy, and practices across care settings. Emphasizing the multidisciplinary and interprofessional practice approaches used to deliver care, this book is an essential learning tool for students interested in medicine, nursing, social work, allied health professions, case management, health care administration, and gerontology. As the population of older adults grows, the authors ask, how can we best meet the needs of older adults and their families in the most effective, cost-conscious way while honoring their care choices?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCommunity health services for older peoplezUnited States. 0aHome care serviceszUnited States. 0aOlder peoplexCarezUnited States. 0aOlder peoplexMedical carezUnited States. 0aOlder peoplexServices forzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aDabelko-Schoeny, Holly, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFields, Noelle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGaugler, Joseph E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/ande1776840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231546997423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231546997.jpg  a978-3-11-060660-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles